definition.value: A leavening agent is any one of a number of substances used in doughs and batters that cause a foaming action (gas bubbles) that lightens and softens the mixture.
A sweet chocolate-flavored paste which is eaten mostly spread on breads and toasts or similar grain items such as waffles, pancakes, muffins, and pitas.
A chewy, firm pastille-type sweet similar to a gumdrop without the sugar coating, originating from the United Kingdom.

A type of drink containing sugar and stimulant compounds, usually caffeine, which is marketed as providing mental and physical stimulation (marketed as "energy", but distinct from food energy). They may or may not be carbonated and may also contain other sweeteners, herbal extracts, taurine, and amino acids.
The immersion of raw food in a stock (or sauce) composed variously of paprika, oregano, salt, garlic, and vinegar to preserve and enhance its flavor.
A melon harvested from the horned melon plant.
A small, savory, deep-fried round ball made from cornmeal-based batter. Hushpuppies are frequently served as a side dish with seafood and other deep-fried foods.
A yogurt prepared with soy milk.
A food product not including meat and animal tissue products (such as gelatin or animal-derived rennet).
A fruit of the Cupuaçu plant (Theobroma grandiflorum).
A fruit of the shea tree.
A food product derived from the fruit or seed of the shea tree.
The seed of a shea fruit.

A very thin unleavened dough used for making pastries such as baklava and börek in Middle Eastern and Balkan cuisines. Filo-based pastries are made by layering many sheets of filo brushed with oil or butter; the pastry is then baked.
Soybean material ground into a thick liquid, to which gums are added to create a substance resembling real cream found in mammalian milk.
A semidried sausage traditionally made in Southern Germany, Austria, Switzerland, and Alsace.
A liquid prepared for consumption

A process which takes in some food material from an individual or community of plant or animal organisms in a given context and time, and outputs a precursor or consumable food product. This may include a part of an organism or the whole, and may involve killing the organism.

This includes harvesting from plants, hunting a deer, or milking process of a cow.  The food is derived from part or whole of a single organism species (with perhaps a few exceptions, such as lichen).
A variety of banana plant native to Micronesia

"Eating one of these small bananas (about 100 g) covers the vitamin A requirement for 2 days. The Cavendish variety, on the other hand, contains almost no vitamin A. Growing vitamin A-rich banana varieties in more countries could contribute to a decline in global vitamin A deficiency." [http://www.fao.org/zhc/detail-events/en/c/446573/]
A seed of a peanut plant (Arachis hypogaea).
A roasted peanut pod.
A traditional Japanese seasoning produced by fermenting soybeans with salt and kōji (the fungus Aspergillus oryzae) and sometimes rice, barley, seaweed or other ingredients.

Steel-cut oats (US) are groats (the inner kernel with the inedible hull removed) of whole oats which have been chopped into two or three pinhead-sized pieces (hence the names; "steel-cut" comes from the steel blades).
An oil made out of soybeans genetically modified to produce relatively low levels of linolenic acid in comparison to other soybeans.
Palm kernel oil which has been partly or fully hydrogenated.
A fat used in the confectionery industry for making chocolate, candies, and baked goods. Confectionery fats must remain relatively stable during storage.
Coconut oil which has been partly or completely hydrogenated.
A bakery filling containing a significant proportion of fat - usually 30% but ranging up to 60%.

Winterization of oil is a process that uses a solvent and cold temperatures to separate lipids and other desired oil compounds from waxes. Winterization is a type of fractionation, the general process of separating the triglycerides found in fats and oils, using the difference in their melting points, solubility, and volatility.
Poppyseed oil is an edible oil from poppy seeds (specifically seeds of Papaver somniferum, the opium poppy).
A vegetable oil extracted from the seeds of tomatoes.
Oil extracted from walnuts (from the Juglans regia tree).
Oil pressed from the kernels of the Prunus armeniaca (apricot). Apricot kernels have an oil content of 40-50%
Oil pressed from hazelnuts. It is strongly flavoured and used as a cooking oil.
A fruit of the Cupuaçu plant (Theobroma grandiflorum).
A butter obtained from the nutmeg nut by expression. It is semisolid, reddish-brown in colour, and has the taste and smell of nutmeg itself.
Oil extracted from the seed of ucuhuba plants (Virola surinamensis).
A partly hydrogenated oil made from soybeans.
Oil extracted from the hard outer brown layer of rice called chaff (rice husk).
A partly hydrogenated oil made from soybeans.
A type of tomato bred for sauce and packing purposes.

A distilled, highly alcoholic beverage (45–74% ABV / 90–148 U.S. proof). It is an anise-flavoured spirit derived from botanicals, including the flowers and leaves of Artemisia absinthium ("grand wormwood"), together with green anise, sweet fennel, and other medicinal and culinary herbs.
Muesli is a cold breakfast cereal dish based on rolled oats and ingredients like grains, nuts, seeds and fresh or dried fruits.
A dessert pastry consisting of a filled brioche.
Bolognese sauce is a meat-based sauce in Italian cuisine, typical of the city of Bologna
A beef stew braised in red wine, often red Burgundy, and beef stock, generally flavoured with carrots, onions, garlic, and a bouquet garni, and garnished with pearl onions, mushrooms, and bacon.
Small skewer or spit on which small pieces of meat, fish or vegetables are roasted or broiled
A small skewer of meat
